photo.title: Full moon over Tromsø, Norway (explored)

description._content:
Another view from my hotel window as the full moon was slowly rising over a blue hour city. Here we are looking from Tromsø island, where most of the city is, towards the mainland with Tromsø's most famous landmark, the Arctic Cathedral (1965). The church is not actually a cathedral, and the Tromsø cathedral itself is a wooden building in the centre.
Behind the church is a cable car to the top of Mt. Storstein. Unfortunately it was undergoing repairs when I was there, so I will have to return.
Tromsø is one of the largest cities to be found north of the Arctic Circle (approx. 75000 inh). It grew up as an Arctic trade centre and it was here that people like Roald Amundsen prepared for their trip to conquer the South Pole.

[#8 on explore 24/12/16]

photo.title: Single Frog Eye

description._content: A tiny frog's one eye is visible just above the surface of the duckweed covered water.  This is from back in the summer during one of the mornings I spend photographing these interesting creatures.  It's always fun when the pond is covered in green duckweed and you get to watch frogs randomly pop through the surface.  To get photos like this is a relatively easy process.  Find a pond with lots of frogs, walk up to the edge, scare them all into the water, lay down along the shoreline and wait patiently.  Usually within 10-15 minutes they will start surfacing right nearby and you can shoot away.  Taken at Palmyra Cove Nature Park in southern New Jersey. ~ 8/19/16 - ¹⁄₁₆₀ sec at f/5.6 - ISO400 ~ 420 mm ~ 300 mm f/4

photo.title: Aputi - Explored

description._content:
It is often said that the inuits have a 100 words for snow. This number may be an exaggeration, but they do in fact have multiple words for snow and ice in the Inuktitut dialect. Qanik means falling snow, while qanittaq means freshly fallen snow. Aputi means snow on the ground. Pukak means crystalline snow. qinu means the slushy ice by the sea. Siku means ice in general, while sikuaq means that thin layer of ice that first forms over a puddle.

Merry Christmas and Happy holidays everyone. Here's to a white Christmas :)

thecanadianencyclopedia.ca

photo.title: Fence on Burrator shoreline_NK2_3102

description._content:
Though I think it makes a good subject for a photograph, this fence is not a welcome sight. It is to prevent people from getting to the shoreline of the Longstone peninsular on Burrator Reservoir. 

This was one of my very favourite areas to walk when I needed to get away for an hour to 'chill out'. Now I'm barred!  Only those with a fishing licence are permitted to this area.
I was devastated when I first discovered this barrier, and I'm sure many others will share my dismay as it's one of the nicest spots around the lake.

Thanks for any comments and faves - always very much appreciated :-)

 AND I wish all my FLICKR friends a very Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year. Thank you all for your kind comments, faves and support in 2016 :-)

description._content: This WHITE-HEADED BUFFALO WEAVER or white-faced buffalo-weaver  is a species of passerine bird in the family Ploceidae native to East Africa.....The buffalo part of its name derives from its habit of following the African buffalo, feeding on disturbed insects.....Wikipedia.

photo.title: After the Blizzard, Bismarck, North Dakota

description._content:
This is my dad's back yard after the first of several big blizzards they ended up getting. The one after this actually shut down most of the interstate for a few days, which is very unusual in ND. It also closed schools, which is even more unusual. North Dakota is set, yet again, for a huge blizzard over Christmas. It's a banner year for snow in the state!
p.s. I lived on this property from ages 11-19, and had to haul water across the three acres to each and every one of those trees when they were tiny. It was zero fun. They sure look great now though!
